# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hull-watercraft
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hull-watercraft/30th-century-bc] The **30th century BC** was a time period that lasted from the year 3000 BC to 2901 BC.
[src:hull-watercraft/aframax] An **Aframax** vessel is an oil tanker with a deadweight between 80,000 and 120,000 metric tonnes.
[src:hull-watercraft/aframax] The term is based on the **Average Freight Rate Assessment** (**AFRA**), a tanker rate system created in 1954 by Shell Oil to standardize shipping contract terms.
[src:hull-watercraft/aframax] Due to their favorable size, Aframax tankers can serve most ports in the world.
[src:hull-watercraft/aframax] These vessels serve regions that do not have very large ports or offshore oil terminals to accommodate Very Large Crude Carriers and Ultra-Large Crude Carriers.
[src:hull-watercraft/aframax] Aframax tankers are optimal for short- to medium-haul crude oil transportation.
[src:hull-watercraft/aframax] Aframax class tankers are largely used in the basins of the Black Sea, the North Sea, the Caribbean Sea, the South and East China Seas, and the Mediterranean.
[src:hull-watercraft/aframax] Non–OPEC exporting countries may require the use of this type of vessel because the harbors and canals through which these countries export their oil are too small to accommodate the Suezmax or the larger categories.
[src:hull-watercraft/aframax] An Aframax tanker carries 600,000 barrels of oil as compared to larger tankers that may carry up to 2 million barrels of oil.
[src:hull-watercraft/aftercastle] The **aftercastle** (or **sterncastle**, sometimes **aftcastle**) is the stern structure behind the mizzenmast and above the transom on large sailing ships, such as carracks, caravels, galleons and galleasses.
[src:hull-watercraft/aftercastle] It usually houses the captain's cabin and perhaps additional cabins and is crowned by the poop deck, which on men-of-war provided a heightened platform from which to fire upon other ships; it was also a place of defence in the event of boarding.
[src:hull-watercraft/aftercastle] More common, but much smaller, is the forecastle.
[src:hull-watercraft/aftercastle] The corresponding term *forecastle* today is also used to describe the upper deck of a sailing ship forward of the foremast in general.
[src:hull-watercraft/aftercastle] As sailing ships evolved, the aftercastle gave way to the quarterdeck, whose span ran all the way to the main mast.
[src:hull-watercraft/afterdeck] In naval architecture, an **afterdeck** or **after deck**, or sometimes the **aftdeck**, **aft deck** or **a-deck** is the open deck area toward the stern or aft back part of a ship or boat.
[src:hull-watercraft/afterdeck] The afterdeck can be used for a number of different purposes, yet not all ships have an afterdeck.
[src:hull-watercraft/afterdeck] In place of the afterdeck, a ship may be built with a poop deck, that is a deck that forms the roof of a cabin built in the rear, or "aft", part of the superstructure of a ship; a poop deck is usually higher up than an afterdeck.
[src:hull-watercraft/afterdeck] A ship may have its superstructure or aftercastle located in the stern and thus not have an afterdeck.
[src:hull-watercraft/afterdeck] The stern and afterdeck of a ship are usually more smooth and stable than the bow (front) of the ship in motion.
[src:hull-watercraft/afterdeck] A taffrail is the handrail around the open afterdeck or poop deck.
[src:hull-watercraft/afterdeck] On wooden sailing ships like man-of-war or East Indiaman the taffrail is usually a hand carved wood rail and often highly decorated.
[src:hull-watercraft/air-draft] The vessel's clearance is the distance in excess of the air draft which allows a vessel to pass safely under a bridge or obstacle such as power lines, etc.
[src:hull-watercraft/air-draft] A bridge's "clearance below" is most often noted on charts as measured from the surface of the water to the underside of the bridge at the chart datum Mean High Water (MHW), a less restrictive clearance than Mean Higher High Water (MHHW).
[src:hull-watercraft/air-draft] In 2014, the United States Coast Guard reported that 1.2% of the collisions that it had investigated in the recent past were bridge strikes caused by vessels attempting to pass under structures with insufficient clearance.
[src:hull-watercraft/air-draft] The Bridge of the Americas in Panama limits which ships can traverse the Panama Canal due to its height at 61.3 m (201 ft) above the water.
[src:hull-watercraft/air-draft] New vessels are rarely built not clearing 65 m (213 ft), a height which accommodates all but the largest cruise and container ships.
[src:hull-watercraft/air-draft] The Suez Canal Bridge has a 70-metre (230 ft) clearance over the canal.
[src:hull-watercraft/air-draft] The Bayonne Bridge, an arch bridge connecting New Jersey with New York City, undertook a $1.7 billion modification to raise its roadbed to 66 m (217 ft).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] A **windlass** is a machine used on ships that is used to let-out and heave-up equipment such as a ship's anchor or a fishing trawl.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] On some ships, it may be located in a specific room called the windlass room.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] An **anchor windlass** is a machine that restrains and manipulates the anchor chain on a boat, allowing the anchor to be raised and lowered by means of chain cable.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] A notched wheel engages the links of the chain or the rope.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] A trawl windlass is a similar machine that restrains or manipulates the trawl on a commercial fishing vessel.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The trawl is a sort of big fishing net that is wound on the windlass.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The fishermen either let-out the trawl or heave-up the trawl during fishing operations.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] A brake is provided for additional control.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The windlass is usually powered by an electric or hydraulic motor operating via a gear train.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Technically speaking, the term "windlass" refers only to horizontal winches.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Vertical designs are correctly called capstans.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Horizontal windlasses make use of an integral gearbox and motor assembly, all typically located above-deck, with a horizontal shaft through the unit and wheels for chain and/or rope on either side.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Vertical capstans use a vertical shaft, with the motor and gearbox situated below the winch unit (usually below decks).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Horizontal windlasses offer several advantages.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The unit tends to be more self-contained, protecting the machinery from the corrosive environment found on boats.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The dual wheels also allow two anchors on double rollers to be serviced.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Vertical capstans, for their part, allow the machinery to be placed below decks, thus lowering the center of gravity (important on boats), and also allow a flexible angle of pull (which means rope or chain can be run out to different fair leads).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] It tends to be the case that smaller boats use capstans, and larger boats have windlasses, although this is by no means a hard and fast rule.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] This would occur if the windlass brake has slipped (in a storm, for example) and the cable has reached "the bitter end".
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] This is the origin of the term "to the bitter end".
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] It originally applied in sailing vessels where the cable was a rope, and the windlass or capstan was powered by many sailors below decks.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The wheels on either a vertical or horizontal windlass provide for either chain or line to be engaged.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The wheel for line is termed a warping head, while the chain handling wheel is variously referred to as the gypsy (in the UK) or wildcat (in North America).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] For clarity in communication the generic term chainwheel is often used.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] On small craft a warping drum is sometimes used to handle both chain & rope, although particular care must be taken with sizing and compatibility of line, chain, and windlass, for this feature to work effectively.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] It is important that the chainwheel match the chain size (i.e. the link pitch) closely.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Even a small difference in link size or consistency can cause undue wear on the chainwheel and/or cause the chain to jump off the windlass when the winch is operating, particularly during payout, a runaway condition sometimes referred to as "water spouting" should it occur at high speed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Nowadays, especially on large tankers and cruise ships, the windlass may be split into independent port and starboard units.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] In these cases they are frequently coupled with warping drums (as distinct from warping heads).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] In some of these the warping drums are of the self tensioning or constant tension type.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The mechanical advantage of a windlass is derived from the pulling force being multiplied by wrapping the rope around the drum.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The math for such force phenomena is described by the Capstan equation.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] While many modern windlasses require an external power source, many remain manually driven in the same manner as most sailing boats' winches for sheets.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Powered solutions include steam (antiquated), hydraulics, and electrics.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Electrics are convenient and relatively cheap, but hydraulics may be more efficient and powerful if available.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] In general, windlasses and their power system should be capable of lifting the anchor and all its rode (chain and rope) so that the anchor and rode hang suspended in deep water.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] This task should be within the windlass' rated working pull, not its maximum pull.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] The devil's claw is a device that is used as a chain stopper to grab and hold an anchor chain.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] It consists of a turnbuckle, usually attached at the base of the anchor windlass, and a metal hook with two curved fingers that grab one link of a chain.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] A devil's claw is often used on merchant ships because it is lighter and easier to manage than other types of chain stoppers, such as a pelican hook.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] After hoisting the anchor and setting the windlass brake, the claw is placed on a chain link and the turnbuckle is tightened to take up the tension on the chain.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] If more than one stopper is used, the turnbuckles can be adjusted to evenly distribute the load.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] A devil's claw cannot be released while it is under tension.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] To release it, the tension must first be taken up by the windlass brake.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor-windlass] Then the turnbuckle can be loosened and removed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] An **anchor** is a device, normally made of metal, used to secure a vessel to the bed of a body of water to prevent the craft from drifting due to wind or current.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The word derives from Latin **ancora**, which itself comes from the Greek ἄγκυρα (*ankȳra*).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Anchors can either be temporary or permanent.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Permanent anchors are used in the creation of a mooring, and are rarely moved; a specialist service is normally needed to move or maintain them.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Vessels carry one or more temporary anchors, which may be of different designs and weights.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A sea anchor is a drag device, not in contact with the seabed, used to minimize drift of a vessel relative to the water.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A drogue is a drag device used to slow or help steer a vessel running before a storm in a following or overtaking sea, or when crossing a bar in a breaking sea.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Anchors achieve holding power either by "hooking" into the seabed, or weight, or a combination of the two.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The weight of the anchor chain can be more than that of the anchor and is critical to proper holding.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Permanent moorings use large masses (commonly a block or slab of concrete) resting on the seabed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Semi-permanent mooring anchors (such as mushroom anchors) and large ship's anchors derive a significant portion of their holding power from their weight, while also hooking or embedding in the bottom.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Modern anchors for smaller vessels have metal *flukes* that hook on to rocks on the bottom or bury themselves in soft seabed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The vessel is attached to the anchor by the *rode* (also called a *cable* or a *warp*).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It can be made of rope, chain or a combination of rope and chain.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The ratio of the length of rode to the water depth is known as the scope.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Holding ground is the area of sea floor that holds an anchor, and thus the attached ship or boat.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Different types of anchor are designed to hold in different types of holding ground.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Some bottom materials hold better than others; for instance, hard sand holds well, shell holds poorly.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Holding ground may be fouled with obstacles.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] An anchorage location may be chosen for its holding ground.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In poor holding ground, only the weight of an anchor and chain matters; in good holding ground, it is able to dig in, and the holding power can be significantly higher.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The basic anchoring consists of determining the location, dropping the anchor, laying out the scope, setting the hook, and assessing where the vessel ends up.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The ship seeks a location that is sufficiently protected; has suitable holding ground, enough depth at low tide and enough room for the boat to swing.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The location to drop the anchor should be approached from down wind or down current, whichever is stronger.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] As the chosen spot is approached, the vessel should be stopped or even beginning to drift back.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The anchor should initially be lowered quickly but under control until it is on the bottom (see anchor windlass).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The vessel should continue to drift back, and the cable should be veered out under control (slowly) so it is relatively straight.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Once the desired scope is laid out, the vessel should be gently forced astern, usually using the auxiliary motor but possibly by backing a sail.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A hand on the anchor line may telegraph a series of jerks and jolts, indicating the anchor is dragging, or a smooth tension indicative of digging in.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] As the anchor begins to dig in and resist backward force, the engine may be throttled up to get a thorough set.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Lowering a concentrated, heavy weight down the anchor line – rope or chain – directly in front of the bow to the seabed behaves like a heavy chain rode and lowers the angle of pull on the anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] If the weight is suspended off the seabed it acts as a spring or shock absorber to dampen the sudden actions that are normally transmitted to the anchor and can cause it to dislodge and drag.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In light conditions, a kellet reduces the swing of the vessel considerably.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In heavier conditions these effects disappear as the rode becomes straightened and the weight ineffective.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Known as an "anchor chum weight" or "angel" in the UK.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Using two anchors set approximately 45° apart, or wider angles up to 90°, from the bow is a strong mooring for facing into strong winds.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] To set anchors in this way, first one anchor is set in the normal fashion.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Then, taking in on the first cable as the boat is motored into the wind and letting slack while drifting back, a second anchor is set approximately a half-scope away from the first on a line perpendicular to the wind.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] After this second anchor is set, the scope on the first is taken up until the vessel is lying between the two anchors and the load is taken equally on each cable.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This moor also to some degree limits the range of a vessel's swing to a narrower oval.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Care should be taken that other vessels do not swing down on the boat due to the limited swing range.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] (Not to be mistaken with the *Bahamian moor*, below.) In the *bow and stern* technique, an anchor is set off each the bow and the stern, which can severely limit a vessel's swing range and also align it to steady wind, current or wave conditions.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] One method of accomplishing this moor is to set a bow anchor normally, then drop back to the limit of the bow cable (or to double the desired scope, e.g.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] 8:1 if the eventual scope should be 4:1, 10:1 if the eventual scope should be 5:1, etc.) to lower a stern anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] By taking up on the bow cable the stern anchor can be set.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] After both anchors are set, tension is taken up on both cables to limit the swing or to align the vessel.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Similar to the above, a *Bahamian moor* is used to sharply limit the swing range of a vessel, but allows it to swing to a current.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] One of the primary characteristics of this technique is the use of a swivel as follows: the first anchor is set normally, and the vessel drops back to the limit of anchor cable.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A second anchor is attached to the end of the anchor cable, and is dropped and set.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A swivel is attached to the middle of the anchor cable, and the vessel connected to that.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The vessel now swings in the middle of two anchors, which is acceptable in strong reversing currents, but a wind perpendicular to the current may break out the anchors, as they are not aligned for this load.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Also known as *tandem anchoring*, in this technique two anchors are deployed in line with each other, on the same rode.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] With the foremost anchor reducing the load on the aft-most, this technique can develop great holding power and may be appropriate in "ultimate storm" circumstances.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It does not limit swinging range, and might not be suitable in some circumstances.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] There are complications, and the technique requires careful preparation and a level of skill and experience above that required for a single anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In yachts, a kedge anchor is an anchor carried in addition to the main, or bower, anchor, and usually stowed aft.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Every yacht should carry at least two anchors – the main or *bower* anchor and a second lighter *kedge* anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It is used occasionally when it is necessary to limit the turning circle as the yacht swings when it is anchored, such as in a narrow river or a deep pool in an otherwise shallow area.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Kedge anchors are sometimes used to recover vessels that have run aground.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] For ships, a kedge may be dropped while a ship is underway, or carried out in a suitable direction by a tender or ship's boat to enable the ship to be winched off if aground or swung into a particular heading, or even to be held steady against a tidal or other stream.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Historically, it was of particular relevance to sailing warships that used them to outmaneuver opponents when the wind had dropped but might be used by any vessel in confined, shoal water to place it in a more desirable position, provided she had enough manpower.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] When a vessel is in a narrow channel or on a lee shore so that there is no room to tack the vessel in a conventional manner, an anchor attached to the lee quarter may be dropped from the lee bow.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This is deployed when the vessel is head to wind and has lost headway.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] As the vessel gathers sternway the strain on the cable pivots the vessel around what is now the weather quarter turning the vessel onto the other tack.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The anchor is then normally cut away (the ship's momentum prevents recovery without aborting the maneuver).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The anchors are usually laid in prearranged positions by an anchor tender, and the moored vessel uses its own winches to adjust position and tension.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Similar arrangements are used for some types of single buoy moorings, like the catenary anchor leg mooring (CALM) used for loading and unloading liquid cargoes.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Since all anchors that embed themselves in the bottom require the strain to be along the seabed, anchors can be broken out of the bottom by shortening the rope until the vessel is directly above the anchor; at this point the anchor chain is "up and down", in naval parlance.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] If necessary, motoring slowly around the location of the anchor also helps dislodge it.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Anchors are sometimes fitted with a trip line attached to the crown, by which they can be unhooked from underwater hazards.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The term *aweigh* describes an anchor when it is hanging on the rope and not resting on the bottom.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This is linked to the term *to weigh anchor*, meaning to lift the anchor from the sea bed, allowing the ship or boat to move.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] An anchor is described as *aweigh* when it has been broken out of the bottom and is being hauled up to be *stowed*.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] *Aweigh* should not be confused with *under way*, which describes a vessel that is not *moored* to a dock or *anchored*, whether or not the vessel is moving through the water.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] *Aweigh* is also often confused with *away*, which is incorrect.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The earliest anchors were probably rocks, and many rock anchors have been found dating from at least the Bronze Age.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Pre-European Māori waka (canoes) used one or more hollowed stones, tied with flax ropes, as anchors.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Many modern moorings still rely on a large rock as the primary element of their design.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] However, using pure weight to resist the forces of a storm works well only as a permanent mooring; a large enough rock would be nearly impossible to move to a new location.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The ancient Greeks used baskets of stones, large sacks filled with sand, and wooden logs filled with lead as a weight for their ships.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Influential authors such as Apollonius Rhodius and Stephen of Byzantium also show that they may be made out of wood, Athenaeus also referring to anchors made out of metals.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Such anchors held the vessel merely by their weight and by their friction along the bottom.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Iron was afterwards introduced for the construction of anchors, and an improvement was made by forming them with teeth, or "flukes", to fasten themselves into the bottom.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This is the iconic anchor shape most familiar to non-sailors.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This form has been used since antiquity.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Roman Nemi ships of the 1st century AD used this form.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Viking Ladby ship (probably 10th century) used a fluked anchor of this type, made of iron, which would have had a wooden stock mounted perpendicular to the shank and flukes to make the flukes contact the bottom at a suitable angle to hook or penetrate.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Admiralty Pattern anchor, or simply "Admiralty", also known as a "Fisherman", consists of a central shank with a ring or shackle for attaching the rode (the rope, chain, or cable connecting the ship and the anchor).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] At the other end of the shank there are two arms, carrying the flukes, while the stock is mounted to the shackle end, at ninety degrees to the arms.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] When the anchor lands on the bottom, it generally falls over with the arms parallel to the seabed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] As a strain comes onto the rope, the stock digs into the bottom, canting the anchor until one of the flukes catches and digs into the bottom.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Admiralty Anchor is an entirely independent reinvention of a classical design, as seen in one of the Nemi ship anchors.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This basic design remained unchanged for centuries, with the most significant changes being to the overall proportions, and a move from stocks made of wood to iron stocks in the late 1830s and early 1840s.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Since one fluke always protrudes up from the set anchor, there is a great tendency of the rode to foul the anchor as the vessel swings due to wind or current shifts.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] When this happens, the anchor may be pulled out of the bottom, and in some cases may need to be hauled up to be re-set.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In the mid-19th century, numerous modifications were attempted to alleviate these problems, as well as improve holding power, including one-armed mooring anchors.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The most successful of these *patent anchors*, the Trotman Anchor, introduced a pivot at the centre of the crown where the arms join the shank, allowing the "idle" upper arm to fold against the shank.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] When deployed the lower arm may fold against the shank tilting the tip of the fluke upwards, so each fluke has a tripping palm at its base, to hook on the bottom as the folded arm drags along the seabed, which unfolds the downward oriented arm until the tip of the fluke can engage the bottom.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Handling and storage of these anchors requires special equipment and procedures.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Once the anchor is hauled up to the hawsepipe, the ring end is hoisted up to the end of a timber projecting from the bow known as the cathead.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The crown of the anchor is then hauled up with a heavy tackle until one fluke can be hooked over the rail.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This is known as "catting and fishing" the anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Before dropping the anchor, the fishing process is reversed, and the anchor is dropped from the end of the cathead.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The stockless anchor, patented in England in 1821, represented the first significant departure in anchor design in centuries.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Although their holding-power-to-weight ratio is significantly lower than admiralty pattern anchors, their ease of handling and stowage aboard large ships led to almost universal adoption.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In contrast to the elaborate stowage procedures for earlier anchors, stockless anchors are simply hauled up until they rest with the shank inside the hawsepipes, and the flukes against the hull (or inside a recess in the hull called the anchor box).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] While there are numerous variations, stockless anchors consist of a set of heavy flukes connected by a pivot or ball and socket joint to a shank.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Cast into the crown of the anchor is a set of tripping palms, projections that drag on the bottom, forcing the main flukes to dig in.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Until the mid-20th century, anchors for smaller vessels were either scaled-down versions of admiralty anchors, or simple grapnels.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] As new designs with greater holding-power-to-weight ratios were sought, a great variety of anchor designs have emerged.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Many of these designs are still under patent, and other types are best known by their original trademarked names.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A traditional design, the grapnel is merely a shank (no stock) with four or more tines, also known as a *drag*.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It has a benefit in that, no matter how it reaches the bottom, one or more tines are aimed to set.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In coral, or rock, it is often able to set quickly by hooking into the structure, but may be more difficult to retrieve.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A grapnel is often quite light, and may have additional uses as a tool to recover gear lost overboard.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Its weight also makes it relatively easy to move and carry, however its shape is generally not compact and it may be awkward to stow unless a collapsing model is used.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Grapnels rarely have enough fluke area to develop much hold in sand, clay, or mud.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It is not unknown for the anchor to foul on its own rode, or to foul the tines with refuse from the bottom, preventing it from digging in.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] On the other hand, it is quite possible for this anchor to find such a good hook that, without a trip line from the crown, it is impossible to retrieve.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Francis Herreshoff, this is essentially the same pattern as an admiralty anchor, albeit with small diamond-shaped flukes or palms.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The novelty of the design lay in the means by which it could be broken down into three pieces for stowage.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In use, it still presents all the issues of the admiralty pattern anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Originally designed as a lightweight anchor for seaplanes, this design consists of two plough-like blades mounted to a shank, with a folding stock crossing through the crown of the anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Many manufacturers produce a plough-type anchor, so-named after its resemblance to an agricultural plough.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] All such anchors are copied from the original CQR (*Coastal Quick Release*, or *Clyde Quick Release*, later rebranded as 'secure' by Lewmar), a 1933 design patented in the UK by mathematician Geoffrey Ingram Taylor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Plough anchors stow conveniently in a roller at the bow, and have been popular with cruising sailors and private boaters.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Ploughs can be moderately good in all types of seafloor, though not exceptional in any.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Contrary to popular belief, the CQR's hinged shank is not to allow the anchor to turn with direction changes rather than breaking out, but actually to prevent the shank's weight from disrupting the fluke's orientation while setting.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The hinge can wear out and may trap a sailor's fingers.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Some later plough anchors have a rigid shank, such as the Lewmar's "Delta".
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A plough anchor has a fundamental flaw: like its namesake, the agricultural plough, it digs in but then tends to break out back to the surface.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Plough anchors sometimes have difficulty setting at all, and instead skip across the seafloor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] By contrast, modern efficient anchors tend to be "scoop" types that dig ever deeper.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Delta anchor was derived from the CQR.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It was patented by Philip McCarron, James Stewart, and Gordon Lyall of British marine manufacturer Simpson-Lawrence Ltd in 1992.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It was designed as an advance over the anchors used for floating systems such as oil rigs.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It retains the weighted tip of the CQR but has a much higher fluke area to weight ratio than its predecessor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The designers also eliminated the sometimes troublesome hinge.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It is a plough anchor with a rigid, arched shank.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It is described as *self-launching* because it can be dropped from a bow roller simply by paying out the rode, without manual assistance.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This is an oft copied design with the European Brake and Australian Sarca Excel being two of the more notable ones.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Although it is a plough type anchor, it sets and holds reasonably well in hard bottoms.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] American Richard Danforth invented the Danforth Anchor in the 1940s for use aboard landing craft.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It uses a stock at the crown to which two large flat triangular flukes are attached.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The stock is hinged so the flukes can orient toward the bottom (and on some designs may be adjusted for an optimal angle depending on the bottom type).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Tripping palms at the crown act to tip the flukes into the seabed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The design is a burying variety, and once well set can develop high resistance.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Its lightweight and compact flat design make it easy to retrieve and relatively easy to store; some anchor rollers and hawsepipes can accommodate a fluke-style anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A Danforth does not usually penetrate or hold in gravel or weeds.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In boulders and coral it may hold by acting as a hook.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] If there is much current, or if the vessel is moving while dropping the anchor, it may "kite" or "skate" over the bottom due to the large fluke area acting as a sail or wing.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The FOB HP anchor designed in Brittany in the 1970s is a Danforth variant designed to give increased holding through its use of rounded flukes setting at a 30° angle.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Fortress is an American aluminum alloy Danforth variant that can be disassembled for storage and it features an adjustable 32° and 45° shank/fluke angle to improve holding capability in common sea bottoms such as hard sand and soft mud.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This anchor performed well in a 1989 US Naval Sea Systems Command (NAVSEA) test and in an August 2014 holding power test that was conducted in the soft mud bottoms of the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This claw-shaped anchor was designed by Peter Bruce from Scotland in the 1970s.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Bruce gained his early reputation from the production of large-scale commercial anchors for ships and fixed installations such as oil rigs.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It was later scaled down for small boats, and copies of this popular design abound.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Bruce and its copies, known generically as "claw type anchors", have been adopted on smaller boats (partly because they stow easily on a bow roller) but they are most effective in larger sizes.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Claw anchors are quite popular on charter fleets as they have a high chance of setting on the first try in many bottoms.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] They have the reputation of not breaking out with tide or wind changes, instead slowly turning in the bottom to align with the force.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Bruce anchors can have difficulty penetrating weedy bottoms and grass.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] They offer a fairly low holding-power-to-weight ratio and generally have to be oversized to compete with newer types.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Three time circumnavigator German Rolf Kaczirek invented the Bügel Anker in the 1980s.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Kaczirek wanted an anchor that was self-righting without necessitating a ballasted tip.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Instead, he added a roll bar and switched out the plough share for a flat blade design.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] As none of the innovations of this anchor were patented, copies of it abound.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Alain Poiraud of France introduced the scoop type anchor in 1996.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Similar in design to the Bügel anchor, Poiraud's design features a concave fluke shaped like the blade of a shovel, with a shank attached parallel to the fluke, and the load applied toward the digging end.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It is designed to dig into the bottom like a shovel, and dig deeper as more pressure is applied.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The common challenge with all the scoop type anchors is that they set so well, they can be difficult to weigh.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] These are used where the vessel is permanently or semi-permanently sited, for example in the case of lightvessels or channel marker buoys.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The anchor needs to hold the vessel in all weathers, including the most severe storm, but needs to be lifted only occasionally, at most – for example, only if the vessel is to be towed into port for maintenance.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] An alternative to using an anchor under these circumstances, especially if the anchor need never be lifted at all, may be to use a pile that is driven into the seabed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Permanent anchors come in a wide range of types and have no standard form.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A slab of rock with an iron staple in it to attach a chain to would serve the purpose, as would any dense object of appropriate weight (for instance, an engine block).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Modern moorings may be anchored by augers, which look and act like oversized screws drilled into the seabed, or by barbed metal beams pounded in (or even driven in with explosives) like pilings, or by a variety of other non-mass means of getting a grip on the bottom.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] One method of building a mooring is to use three or more conventional anchors laid out with short lengths of chain attached to a swivel, so no matter which direction the vessel moves, one or more anchors are aligned to resist the force.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The mushroom anchor is suitable where the seabed is composed of silt or fine sand.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It was invented by Robert Stevenson, for use by an 82-ton converted fishing boat, *Pharos*, which was used as a lightvessel between 1807 and 1810 near to Bell Rock whilst the lighthouse was being constructed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It is shaped like an inverted mushroom, the head becoming buried in the silt.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A counterweight is often provided at the other end of the shank to lay it down before it becomes buried.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A mushroom anchor normally sinks in the silt to the point where it has displaced its own weight in bottom material, thus greatly increasing its holding power.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] These anchors are suitable only for a silt or mud bottom, since they rely upon suction and cohesion of the bottom material, which rocky or coarse sand bottoms lack.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The holding power of this anchor is at best about twice its weight until it becomes buried, when it can be as much as ten times its weight.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] They are available in sizes from about 5 kg up to several tons.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A deadweight is an anchor that relies solely on being a heavy weight.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] It is usually just a large block of concrete or stone at the end of the chain.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Its holding power is defined by its weight underwater (i.e., taking its buoyancy into account) regardless of the type of seabed, although suction can increase this if it becomes buried.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Consequently, deadweight anchors are used where mushroom anchors are unsuitable, for example in rock, gravel or coarse sand.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] An advantage of a deadweight anchor over a mushroom is that if it does drag, it continues to provide its original holding force.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The disadvantage of using deadweight anchors in conditions where a mushroom anchor could be used is that it needs to be around ten times the weight of the equivalent mushroom anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Auger anchors can be used to anchor permanent moorings, floating docks, fish farms, etc.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] These anchors, which have one or more slightly pitched self-drilling threads, must be screwed into the seabed with the use of a tool, so require access to the bottom, either at low tide or by use of a diver.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Hence they can be difficult to install in deep water without special equipment.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Weight for weight, augers have a higher holding than other permanent designs, and so can be cheap and relatively easily installed, although difficult to set in extremely soft mud.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] There is a need in the oil-and-gas industry to resist large anchoring forces when laying pipelines and for drilling vessels.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] These anchors are installed and removed using a support tug and pennant/pendant wire.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Some examples are the Stevin range supplied by Vrijhof Ankers.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Large plate anchors such as the Stevmanta are used for permanent moorings.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The elements of anchoring gear include the anchor, the cable (also called a *rode*), the method of attaching the two together, the method of attaching the cable to the ship, charts, and a method of learning the depth of the water.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Vessels may carry a number of anchors: *bower anchors* are the main anchors used by a vessel and normally carried at the bow of the vessel.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A *kedge anchor* is a light anchor used for warping an anchor, also known as *kedging*, or more commonly on yachts for mooring quickly or in benign conditions.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A *stream anchor*, which is usually heavier than a *kedge anchor*, can be used for kedging or warping in addition to temporary mooring and restraining stern movement in tidal conditions or in waters where vessel movement needs to be restricted, such as rivers and channels.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Knowing the location of potential dangers, as well as being useful in estimating the effects of weather and tide in the anchorage, is essential in choosing a good place to drop the hook.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] One can get by without referring to charts, but they are an important tool and a part of good anchoring gear, and a skilled mariner would not choose to anchor without them.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The anchor rode (or "cable" or "warp") that connects the anchor to the vessel is usually made up of chain, rope, or a combination of those.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Smaller craft might use a rope/chain combination or an all chain rode.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] All rodes should have some chain; chain is heavy but it resists abrasion from coral, sharp rocks, or shellfish beds, whereas a rope warp is susceptible to abrasion and can fail in a short time when stretched against an abrasive surface.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The weight of the chain also helps keep the direction of pull on the anchor closer to horizontal, which improves holding, and absorbs part of snubbing loads.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Where weight is not an issue, a heavier chain provides better holding by forming a catenary curve through the water and resting as much of its length on the bottom as would not be lifted by tension of the mooring load.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Any changes to the tension are accommodated by additional chain being lifted or settling on the bottom, and this absorbs shock loads until the chain is straight, at which point the full load is taken by the anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Additional dissipation of shock loads can be achieved by fitting a snubber between the chain and a bollard or cleat on deck.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This also reduces shock loads on the deck fittings, and the vessel usually lies more comfortably and quietly.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Being strong and elastic, nylon rope is the most suitable as an anchor rode.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Polyester (terylene) is stronger but less elastic than nylon.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Both materials sink, so they avoid fouling other craft in crowded anchorages and do not absorb much water.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Neither breaks down quickly in sunlight.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Elasticity helps absorb shock loading, but causes faster abrasive wear when the rope stretches over an abrasive surface, like a coral bottom or a poorly designed chock.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Polypropylene ("polyprop") is not suited to rodes because it floats and is much weaker than nylon, being barely stronger than natural fibres.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Some grades of polypropylene break down in sunlight and become hard, weak, and unpleasant to handle.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Natural fibres such as manila or hemp are still used in developing nations but absorb a lot of water, are relatively weak, and rot, although they do give good handling grip and are often relatively cheap.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Ropes that have little or no elasticity are not suitable as anchor rodes.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Elasticity is partly a function of the fibre material and partly of the rope structure.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] All anchors should have a chain of at least equal to the boat's length.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Some skippers prefer an all chain warp for greater security on coral or sharp edged rock bottoms.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The chain should be shackled to the warp through a steel eye or spliced to the chain using a chain splice.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The shackle pin should be securely wired or moused.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Either galvanized or stainless steel is suitable for eyes and shackles, galvanized steel being the stronger of the two.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Some skippers prefer to add a swivel to the rode.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] There is a school of thought that says this swivel should not be connected to the anchor itself, but be somewhere in the chain.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] However, most skippers connect the swivel directly to the anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Scope is the ratio of length of the rode to the depth of the water measured from the highest point (usually the anchor roller or bow chock) to the seabed, making allowance for the highest expected tide.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] When making this ratio large enough, one can ensure that the pull on the anchor is as horizontal as possible.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This will make it unlikely for the anchor to break out of the bottom and drag, if it was properly embedded in the seabed to begin with.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] When deploying chain, a large enough scope leads to a load that is entirely horizontal, whilst an anchor rode made only of rope will never achieve a strictly horizontal pull.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In moderate conditions, the ratio of rode to water depth should be 4:1 – where there is sufficient swing-room, a greater scope is always better.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] In rougher conditions it should be up to twice this with the extra length giving more stretch and a smaller angle to the bottom to resist the anchor breaking out.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] For example, if the water is 8 metres (26 ft) deep, and the anchor roller is 1 m (3 ft) above the water, then the 'depth' is 9 meters (~30 feet).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The amount of rode to let out in moderate conditions is thus 36 meters (120 feet).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] When using a rope rode, there is a simple way to estimate the scope: The ratio of bow height of the rode to length of rode above the water while lying back hard on the anchor is the same or less than the scope ratio.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The basis for this is simple geometry (Intercept Theorem): The ratio between two sides of a triangle stays the same regardless of the size of the triangle as long as the angles do not change.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Generally, the rode should be between 5 and 10 times the depth to the seabed, giving a scope of 5:1 or 10:1; the larger the number, the shallower the angle is between the cable and the seafloor, and the less upwards force is acting on the anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A 10:1 scope gives the greatest holding power, but also allows for much more drifting about due to the longer amount of cable paid out.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Anchoring with sufficient scope and/or heavy chain rode brings the direction of strain close to parallel with the seabed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] This is particularly important for light, modern anchors designed to bury in the bottom, where scopes of 5:1 to 7:1 are common, whereas heavy anchors and moorings can use a scope of 3:1, or less.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Some modern anchors, such as the Ultra holds with a scope of 3:1; but, unless the anchorage is crowded, a longer scope always reduces shock stresses.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] As a consequence, in deep water the scope needed will be less, whilst in very shallow water the scope must be chosen much larger to achieve the same pulling angle at the anchor shank.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] For this reason, the British Admiralty does not use a linear scope formula, but a square root formula instead.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] A couple of online calculators exist to work out the amount of chain and rope needed to achieve a (possibly nearly) horizontal pull at the anchor shank, and the associated anchor load.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Consequences of failure depend on circumstances, but may include wrecking by being driven aground on a lee shore, a particularly serious risk for sailing vessels without auxiliary propulsion when embayed.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] An anchor frequently appears on the flags and coats of arms of institutions involved with the sea, as well as of port cities and seacoast regions and provinces in various countries.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] There also exists in heraldry the "Anchored Cross", or Mariner's Cross, a stylized cross in the shape of an anchor.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The symbol can be used to signify 'fresh start' or 'hope'.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Mariner's Cross is also referred to as St.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Clement's Cross, in reference to the way this saint was killed (being tied to an anchor and thrown from a boat into the Black Sea in 102).
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] Anchored crosses are occasionally a feature of coats of arms in which context they are referred to by the heraldic terms *anchry* or *ancre*.
[src:hull-watercraft/anchor] The Unicode anchor (Miscellaneous Symbols) is represented by: U+2693 ⚓ ANCHOR.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] A **hull** is the watertight body of a ship, boat, submarine, or flying boat.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The hull may open at the top (such as a dinghy), or it may be fully or partially covered with a deck.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Atop the deck may be a deckhouse and other superstructures, such as a funnel, derrick, or mast.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The line where the hull meets the water surface is called the waterline.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] There is a wide variety of hull types that are chosen for suitability for different usages, the hull shape being dependent upon the needs of the design.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Shapes range from a nearly perfect box, in the case of scow barges, to a needle-sharp surface of revolution in the case of a racing multihull sailboat.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] In a typical modern steel ship, the hull will have watertight decks, and major transverse members called bulkheads.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] There may also be intermediate members such as girders, stringers and webs, and minor members called ordinary transverse frames, frames, or longitudinals, depending on the structural arrangement.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The uppermost continuous deck may be called the "upper deck", "weather deck", "spar deck", "main deck", or simply "deck".
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The particular name given depends on the context—the type of ship or boat, the arrangement, or even where it sails.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] In a typical wooden sailboat, the hull is constructed of wooden planking, supported by transverse frames (often referred to as ribs) and bulkheads, which are further tied together by longitudinal stringers or ceiling.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Often but not always there is a centerline longitudinal member called a keel.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] In fiberglass or composite hulls, the structure may resemble wooden or steel vessels to some extent, or be of a monocoque arrangement.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] In many cases, composite hulls are built by sandwiching thin fiber-reinforced skins over a lightweight but reasonably rigid core of foam, balsa wood, impregnated paper honeycomb, or other material.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Perhaps the earliest proper hulls were built by the Ancient Egyptians, who by 3000 BC knew how to assemble wooden planks into a hull.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] At present, the most widely used form is the round bilge hull.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] With a small payload, such a craft has less of its hull below the waterline, giving less resistance and more speed.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] With a greater payload, resistance is greater and speed lower, but the hull's outward bend provides smoother performance in waves.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] As such, the inverted bell shape is a popular form used with planing hulls.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] A chined hull does not have a smooth rounded transition between bottom and sides.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Instead, its contours are interrupted by sharp angles where predominantly longitudinal panels of the hull meet.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The sharper the intersection (the more acute the angle), the "harder" the chine.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] More than one chine per side is possible.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The Cajun "pirogue" is an example of a craft with hard chines.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Benefits of this type of hull include potentially lower production cost and a (usually) fairly flat bottom, making the boat faster at planing.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] A hard chined hull resists rolling (in smooth water) more than does a hull with rounded bilges (the chine creates turbulence and drag resisting the rolling motion, as it moves through the water, the rounded-bilge provides less flow resistance around the turn).
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] In rough seas, this can make the boat roll more, as the motion drags first down, then up, on a chine: round-bilge boats are more seakindly in waves, as a result.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Each of these chine hulls has its own unique characteristics and use.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The flat-bottom hull has high initial stability but high drag.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] To counter the high drag, hull forms are narrow and sometimes severely tapered at bow and stern.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] This leads to poor stability when heeled in a sailboat.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] This is often countered by using heavy interior ballast on sailing versions.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] They are best suited to sheltered inshore waters.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Early racing power boats were fine forward and flat aft.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] This produced maximum lift and a smooth, fast ride in flat water, but this hull form is easily unsettled in waves.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The multi-chine hull approximates a curved hull form.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] It has less drag than a flat-bottom boat.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Multi chines are more complex to build but produce a more seaworthy hull form.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] V or arc-bottom chine boats have a V shape between 6° and 23°.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The flatter shape of a 6-degree hull will plane with less wind or a lower-horsepower engine but will pound more in waves.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The deep V form (between 18 and 23 degrees) is only suited to high-powered planing boats.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] They require more powerful engines to lift the boat onto the plane but give a faster, smoother ride in waves.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Displacement chined hulls have more wetted surface area, hence more drag, than an equivalent round-hull form, for any given displacement.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Smooth curve hulls are hulls that use, just like the curved hulls, a centreboard, or an attached keel.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Semi round bilge hulls are somewhat less round.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The advantage of the semi-round is that it is a nice middle between the S-bottom and chined hull.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Typical examples of a semi-round bilge hull can be found in the Centaur and Laser sailing dinghies.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] S-bottom hulls are sailing boat hulls with a midships transverse half-section shaped like an *s*.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] In the s-bottom, the hull has round bilges and merges smoothly with the keel, and there are no sharp corners on the hull sides between the keel centreline and the sheer line.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Boats with this hull form may have a long fixed deep keel, or a long shallow fixed keel with a centreboard swing keel inside.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Ballast may be internal, external, or a combination.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] This hull form was most popular in the late 19th and early to mid 20th centuries.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Examples of small sailboats that use this s-shape are the Yngling and Randmeer.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Midship coefficient (**Cm** or **Cx**) is the cross-sectional area (Ax) of the slice at midships (or at the largest section for Cx) divided by beam x draft.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] It displays the ratio of the largest underwater section of the hull to a rectangle of the same overall width and depth as the underwater section of the hull.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] This defines the fullness of the underbody.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] A low Cm indicates a cut-away mid-section and a high Cm indicates a boxy section shape.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Prismatic coefficient (**Cp**) is the volume (V) divided by LWLx Ax.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] It displays the ratio of the immersed volume of the hull to a volume of a prism with equal length to the ship and cross-sectional area equal to the largest underwater section of the hull (midship section).
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] This is used to evaluate the distribution of the volume of the underbody.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] A low or fine Cp indicates a full mid-section and fine ends, a high or full Cp indicates a boat with fuller ends.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Planing hulls and other highspeed hulls tend towards a higher Cp.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Waterplane coefficient (**Cw**) is the waterplane area divided by LWL x BWL.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] The waterplane coefficient expresses the fullness of the waterplane, or the ratio of the waterplane area to a rectangle of the same length and width.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] A low Cw figure indicates fine ends and a high Cw figure indicates fuller ends.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Use of computer-aided design has superseded paper-based methods of ship design that relied on manual calculations and lines drawing.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] Since the early 1990s, a variety of commercial and freeware software packages specialized for naval architecture have been developed that provide 3D drafting capabilities combined with calculation modules for hydrostatics and hydrodynamics.
[src:hull-watercraft/hull-watercraft] These may be referred to as geometric modeling systems for naval architecture.
